==German==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|gmh|de}} {{term|sameztac|sam(e)ztac|lang=gmh}}, from {{etyl|goh|de}} {{term|sambaztag|lang=goh}}, from Gothic {{term/t|goh|*sambatō}}, from Late Greek {{term|σαμβατος|tr=sambatos|lang=grc}} ‘sabbath’ (compare Old French {{term|sambedi|lang=fro}}, Romansch {{term|somda|lang=rm}}).

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈzamstaːk/|lang=de}} {{a|standard}}
* {{IPA|/ˈzamstax/|lang=de}} {{a|northern and central Germany; chiefly colloquial}}
* {{audio|Samstag.ogg|Samstag|lang=de}}

===Noun===
{{de-noun|m|Samstags|gen2=Samstages|Samstage}}

# {{context|now dominant except in former [[East Germany]]|lang=de}} [[Saturday]]

====Usage notes====
''Samstag'' is the only common word for “Saturday” in western Germany, southern Germany, Austria, and Switzerland (in standard usage). See {{term|Sonnabend|lang=de}} for information on this (declining) synonym.

